        <head xml:id="pl-l4d1c6-Hd1e109">Capitulum 6</head>
        <head xml:id="pl-l4d1c6-Hd1e112" type="question-title">
          On the difference between the old and new sacraments
        </head>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d1c6-d1e115">
          Now it stands to see the distance between the old and new sacraments, 
          as we call those things sacraments which in ancient times were signifying holy things, 
          like sacrifices and oblations and things of this type.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d1c6-d1e118">
          But
          <ref xml:id="pl-l4d1c6-Raqiads" corresp="#pl-l4d1c6-Qd1e123">
            <name ref="#Augustine">Augustine</name>
          </ref>
          assigns a difference 
          between these old and new sacraments saying, 
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d1c6-Qd1e123">
              because those things were only promising and signifying, 
              but these things give salvation
            </quote>
            <bibl>Augustinus, Enarrationes in Psalmos, 73, n. 2 (PL 36, 931)</bibl>
          </cit>. 
        </p>
      </div>
